fucker, explain that code for me!
This code appears to be a struct in Rust. It represents an exchange rate and includes two properties (`data` and `valor`) representing the name of the currency and its value, respectively.

Here's what each part does:

1. `struct`: Declares that you want to create a new type called "ExchangeRate."
2. `ExchangeRate { ... }`: Specifies the fields of this struct. The struct needs at least two fields for it to be usable; in this case, they are both strings (`data` and `valor`).

In Rust, everything is typically defined as structs or enums. Structs (singular) allow you to create a collection of related variables with their respective names while also providing functionality using functions. This code defines a struct that will represent an exchange rate. You can see more about the details of this process by checking the [Rust documentation](https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/struct_types.html#constructors).

In Rust, you'll often define structs with many fields and use them to structure data like databases or files, as they are very flexible in terms of organizing structured information and functionality.
